com.pcloud.sdk

Interface ApiClient


  • public interface ApiClient
    The general interface that exposes pCloud API's methods.

    The class is a factory for Call objects which can be used to execute certain operations on a pCloud account.

    The ApiClient is designed with reuse in mind, it's best used when created once and shared among code using it, mainly due to used connection and thread pooling.

    • Users should configure and create instances through the ApiClient.Builder interface.
    • Builder instances can be created via the PCloudSdk.newClientBuilder() method or from an existing ApiClient instance through the newBuilder() method.
    • Shared instance's configuration can be changed by using the newBuilder() method that will return a pre-configured builder.
    • There is no explicit need to call shutdown(), any idle threads and connections will automatically get closed once not used anymore.
    • All methods return non-null Call instances.
    • All methods are thread-safe.
    • All calls resulting in a collection of objects, return unmodifiable Collection-derived objects.

    Bear in mind that shutting down a ApiClient instance will also affect all instances sharing the underlying resources.

      • createFile

        Call<RemoteFile> createFile(long folderId,
                            java.lang.String filename,
                            DataSource data,
                            java.util.Date modifiedDate,
                            ProgressListener listener)
        Create a new file.

        Creates a new file with the specified name in the specified folder.

        If set, the modifiedDate parameter will be set as the last modification date of the file.

        The provided DataSource object will be used to populate the file's contents.

        If a ProgressListener is provided, it will be notified on every n bytes uploaded, as set per ApiClient.Builder.progressCallbackThreshold(long)

        Method is called with a UploadOptions.DEFAULT argument.

        To create an empty file, call the method with a DataSource.EMPTY argument.

        For more information, see the related documentation page.

        Parameters:
        folderId - The id of the folder you would like to create the file.
        filename - The file name. Must not be null.
        data - DataSource object providing the file content. Must not be null.
        modifiedDate - The last modification date to be used. If set to null, the upload date will be used instead.
        listener - The listener to be used to notify about upload progress. If null, no progress will be reported.
        Returns:
        Call resulting in the new file's metadata
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null filename argument.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null data argument.
        See Also:
        DataSource, ProgressListener, UploadOptions

      • createFile

        Call<RemoteFile> createFile(long folderId,
                            java.lang.String filename,
                            DataSource data,
                            java.util.Date modifiedDate,
                            ProgressListener listener,
                            UploadOptions uploadOptions)
        Create a new file.

        Creates a new file with the specified name in the specified folder.

        If set, the modifiedDate parameter will be set as the last modification date of the file.

        The provided DataSource object will be used to populate the file's contents.

        If a ProgressListener is provided, it will be notified on every n bytes uploaded, as set per ApiClient.Builder.progressCallbackThreshold(long)

        Method uses the supplied UploadOptions, possible constant for usage are UploadOptions.DEFAULT, UploadOptions.OVERRIDE_FILE, UploadOptions.PARTIAL_UPLOAD.

        To create an empty file, call the method with a DataSource.EMPTY argument.

        For more information, see the related documentation page.

        Parameters:
        folderId - The id of the folder you would like to create the file.
        filename - The file name. Must not be null.
        data - DataSource object providing the file content. Must not be null.
        modifiedDate - The last modification date to be used. If set to null, the upload date will be used instead.
        listener - The listener to be used to notify about upload progress. If null, no progress will be reported.
        uploadOptions - UploadOptions to be used for the file creation. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        Call resulting in the new file's metadata
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null filename argument.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null data argument.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null uploadOptions argument.
        See Also:
        DataSource, ProgressListener, UploadOptions

        sink - the sink that will receive the data. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        a void Call which will return on success, or report an error otherwise.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null fileLink argument.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null sink argument.
        See Also:
        DataSink, ProgressListener, FileLink

      • download

        Call<java.lang.Void> download(FileLink fileLink,
                              DataSink sink,
                              ProgressListener listener)
        Download a FileLink to a specified destination.

        This call will get attempt to download the contents of the file that the provided fileLink object was created for, optionally notifying about the progress via a provided ProgressListener. The content bytes will be delivered though the DataSink object.

        See ApiClient.Builder.progressCallbackThreshold(long) for details on how to control the progress notifications rate.

        If set via ApiClient.Builder.callbackExecutor(Executor), the progress listener's methods will be scheduled on the provided Executor.

        Refer to the file links documentation page for details on any ApiError errors.

        Parameters:
        fileLink - the file link to be downloaded. Must not be null.
        sink - the sink that will receive the data. Must not be null.
        listener - an optional listener that will get notified on progress. If null, no progress will be reported.
        Returns:
        a void Call which will return on success, or report an error otherwise.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null fileLink argument.
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null sink argument.
        See Also:
        DataSink, ProgressListener, FileLink

      • download

        Call<okio.BufferedSource> download(RemoteFile file)
        Get the content of a specified remote file.

        This call is a shorthand for obtaining a FileLink object via createFileLink(RemoteFile, DownloadOptions) with DownloadOptions.DEFAULT, then using it with the download(FileLink) method.

        Refer to the file links documentation page for details on any ApiError errors.

        NOTE: It is the caller's responsibility to close the resulting BufferedSource object or resource leaks will occur.

        Parameters:
        file - target file. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        Call which results in a bytes source
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - on a null file argument.
        See Also:
        createFileLink(long, DownloadOptions), download(FileLink)
